1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,300
 So, the last topic we'll talk about here in object orientation is the notion of inheritance.

2
00:00:05,300 --> 00:00:11,800
 And this is a form of code reuse, and it's one of the more advanced aspects of object-oriented programming.

3
00:00:11,800 --> 00:00:16,400
 So, just kind of understand what it is at a high level, and then you know where to come back to

4
00:00:16,400 --> 00:00:19,960
 when you need to learn a bit more about inheritance.

5
00:00:19,960 --> 00:00:23,800
 So, the idea is, instead of making a new class from scratch,

6
00:00:23,800 --> 00:00:26,760
 we actually make a new class by starting with an existing class.

7
00:00:26,760 --> 00:00:31,260
 We are extending it, or another word for this is subclassing.

8
00:00:31,260 --> 00:00:36,300
 And it's sort of a situation where you're like, I've got this code, and I've got this data,

9
00:00:36,300 --> 00:00:40,660
 and I just need to add a few things to it, and then I'll have a whole new thing.

10
00:00:40,660 --> 00:00:45,700
 And as you design objects and what we call object hierarchies, you often do this.

11
00:00:45,700 --> 00:00:50,300
 And it's a form of sort of real clever code reuse.

12
00:00:50,300 --> 00:00:56,300
 But again, don't necessarily think that you're supposed to know when to use this or why to use this.

13
00:00:56,300 --> 00:01:00,200
 Right now, it's just terminology, okay, just terminology.

14
00:01:00,200 --> 00:01:02,700
 We have what call these as parent-child relationships.

15
00:01:02,700 --> 00:01:07,300
 The original class is called a parent, and the new class is called the child class.

16
00:01:07,300 --> 00:01:10,500
 So, subclasses are another word for this.

17
00:01:10,500 --> 00:01:12,600
 You have a class, and then you subclass it.

18
00:01:12,600 --> 00:01:19,200
 I think extending and inheriting and parent-child are probably better ways of expressing it than subclassing.

19
00:01:19,200 --> 00:01:20,600
 So, here's a bit of code.

20
00:01:20,600 --> 00:01:22,600
 Let's take a look at this.

21
00:01:22,600 --> 00:01:27,400
 This code's unchanged, it's the party animal code that we've been saying all along.

22
00:01:27,400 --> 00:01:30,800
 It's the one that we construct and put a name in.

23
00:01:30,800 --> 00:01:32,800
 And now what we're going to do is extend it.

24
00:01:32,800 --> 00:01:36,800
 And so, you'll notice that this code down here is the part that's doing the extending.

25
00:01:36,800 --> 00:01:43,100
 So, we're making a new class, football fan, and by putting in parentheses before the colon, party animal,

26
00:01:43,100 --> 00:01:50,500
 that says football fan inherits everything that is party animal, meaning the X, the name, the init, the party,

27
00:01:50,500 --> 00:01:55,500
 all those methods and data are sitting there, and now we're going to add a new variable.

28
00:01:55,500 --> 00:02:01,300
 So, football fan has, in addition to all those other variables, has points, and it has a touchdown method.

29
00:02:01,300 --> 00:02:05,900
 And we add seven to the points, and then we call the party, and that does that.

30
00:02:05,900 --> 00:02:12,800
 So, this is calling this method, because football fan includes X, name, and party, and init, and everything,

31
00:02:12,800 --> 00:02:14,700
 and all this stuff, this constructor.

32
00:02:14,700 --> 00:02:20,200
 So, this football fan is really an amalgamation of all these things together.

33
00:02:20,200 --> 00:02:24,000
 Party animal is just this stuff, right?

34
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:25,700
 And so, we still have two classes.

35
00:02:25,700 --> 00:02:26,800
 We don't just have one.

36
00:02:26,800 --> 00:02:29,000
 We didn't erase the party animal class.

37
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:31,400
 And so, we take a look at the code that we can run here.

38
00:02:31,400 --> 00:02:34,500
 We can say, oh, okay, let's make a party animal, Sally.

39
00:02:34,500 --> 00:02:43,200
 And so, that constructs an object like this, and then stores that in S, with an X starting out at zero.

40
00:02:43,200 --> 00:02:49,900
 And then we call S party, oops, better change that color, starts out at zero.

41
00:02:49,900 --> 00:02:53,500
 And then we call the party method, and that changes it to one, okay?

42
00:02:53,500 --> 00:02:57,900
 And so, this is, this bit of code, it's as if this part doesn't matter at all,

43
00:02:57,900 --> 00:02:59,600
 because it is a party animal.

44
00:02:59,600 --> 00:03:01,000
 It's not a football fan.

45
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:08,900
 But now, if we take a look at this code down here, take this code down here,

46
00:03:08,900 --> 00:03:12,800
 we're going to construct a football fan, and pass in gym.

47
00:03:12,800 --> 00:03:16,300
 So, that actually uses the underscore, init, from party animal,

48
00:03:16,300 --> 00:03:19,600
 because we extended party animal to make football fan.

49
00:03:19,600 --> 00:03:22,400
 So, we inherited all of the good that was in there.

50
00:03:22,400 --> 00:03:26,600
 So, there it's going to make a name, a variable X, which is going to start at zero,

51
00:03:26,600 --> 00:03:31,900
 a variable name that's going to have gym in it, and a variable points that's going to have a zero in it.

52
00:03:31,900 --> 00:03:37,500
 So, this J variable has more things in it than the S variable has.

53
00:03:37,500 --> 00:03:46,000
 And so, we can call the J party, and if we call J party, that goes here and adds one to X, right?

54
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:49,000
 So, that adds one to X, and then we call J touchdown.

55
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:54,700
 Well, that comes down in here, and adds seven to the points, right?

56
00:03:54,700 --> 00:03:56,700
 And then calls party within us.

57
00:03:56,700 --> 00:04:03,300
 And so, self.party is the current object, i.e. self and J are the same thing, right?

58
00:04:03,300 --> 00:04:09,700
 Self.party, and then it goes up here, and passes self in, and it adds one to the X.

59
00:04:09,700 --> 00:04:12,000
 In this case, of this J variable.

60
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:14,300
 So, this becomes two.

61
00:04:14,300 --> 00:04:19,400
 And that's where it prints out, it prints out, you know, seven and two, and away you go.

62
00:04:19,400 --> 00:04:27,700
 And so, it's a way for you to kind of take all this stuff and stuff it into a class by making a new class,

63
00:04:27,700 --> 00:04:32,600
 and just add the extending bits, the bits that are in addition to the other stuff.

64
00:04:32,600 --> 00:04:37,500
 So, like I said, inheritance is a powerful and wonderful concept.

65
00:04:37,500 --> 00:04:46,500
 It's a form of, excellent form of reuse, but basically, the whole purpose of this lecture was

66
00:04:46,500 --> 00:04:51,700
 so that I could in the future just use these words, and you would understand them as compared to,

67
00:04:51,700 --> 00:04:55,900
 I just want to say method, and I've been saying method all along in this high time that I defined it.

68
00:04:55,900 --> 00:04:58,600
 So, let's just review one last time.

69
00:04:58,600 --> 00:05:04,100
 Class is a template, it is not actually a thing, it is a shape of a thing.

70
00:05:04,100 --> 00:05:08,300
 And we define it and say, when we make one of these things, it's going to have these variables in it,

71
00:05:08,300 --> 00:05:10,400
 it's going to have these methods in it.

72
00:05:10,400 --> 00:05:15,800
 Attributes, variables within a class, a method is a function that's inside of a class.

73
00:05:15,800 --> 00:05:20,200
 Object is once we construct a class, we get back an object.

74
00:05:20,200 --> 00:05:25,200
 And so, object here is the snowman cookies.

75
00:05:25,200 --> 00:05:28,200
 Class is the snowman cookie cutter.

76
00:05:28,200 --> 00:05:37,000
 And a constructor is a bit of code that sets up our object, our instance, when it first is created.

77
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:44,100
 And inheritance is this ability to create a new class, but take all and import and affect all the capabilities

78
00:05:44,100 --> 00:05:46,300
 of an existing class.

79
00:05:46,300 --> 00:05:50,800
 So, object-oriented is awesome.

80
00:05:50,800 --> 00:05:54,700
 For the rest of this class, we're not going to write any object code, we're not going to use class at all,

81
00:05:54,700 --> 00:05:59,000
 but we're going to use objects, and literally, you've been using objects from the beginning of this course.

82
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:08,800
 As soon as you said print, whoops, as soon as you said, you know, x equals high, that's an object.

83
00:06:08,800 --> 00:06:14,200
 And as soon as you said x.upper, you were calling a method, right?

84
00:06:14,200 --> 00:06:16,400
 You've been calling a method all along.

85
00:06:16,400 --> 00:06:24,500
 When you're doing something like fh equals open, this thing you're getting back, that's an object.

86
00:06:24,500 --> 00:06:29,900
 And then you do fh.read or whatever, you're calling a method in the dot operator.

87
00:06:29,900 --> 00:06:32,100
 So you've been using objects all along.

88
00:06:32,100 --> 00:06:38,100
 I now am just finally explaining to you when I say call the read method, or call the upper method,

89
00:06:38,100 --> 00:06:40,600
 or what's this little dot and why is that there?

90
00:06:40,600 --> 00:06:48,600
 So again, it's time for us to understand that, but it will take you a long time before you encounter a problem

91
00:06:48,600 --> 00:06:53,800
 that's large enough where, as part of your solution, you're going to make a new object.

92
00:06:53,800 --> 00:06:55,800
 But when you do, it's really a powerful thing.

93
00:06:55,800 --> 00:07:01,200
 I mean, it's a really bad idea for me as a teacher to say, oh, write a bunch of objects.

94
